{"cursor":"13362","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Hard science fiction' is a category of science fiction characterized by an\nemphasis on scientific or technical detail, or on scientific accuracy, or on\nboth. {{cite book |last=Nicholls |first=Peter\n|editor=John Clute, Peter Nicholls |title=The Encyclopedia of Science\nFiction|edition= |year=1993 |publisher= |location= |isbn= |pages= |chapter=Hard\nSF }} {{cite book |last=Wolfe |first=Gary K.\n|title=Critical Terms for Science Fiction and Fantasy: A Glossary and Guide to\nScholarship|year=1986 |publisher= |location= |isbn= |pages= |chapter=Hard\nScience Fiction }} The term was first used in print in 1957 by P. Schuyler\nMiller in a review of John W. Campbell, Jr.'s [[Islands of Space]] in\n[[Astounding Science Fiction]]. {{cite web\n|url=http://www.jessesword.com/sf/view/1674 |title=hard science fiction n. |accessdate=2007-10-\n07 |date=2005-07-25 |work=Science fiction citations |publisher=Jesse's word\n|quote=Earliest cite: P. Schuyler Miller in Astounding Science Fiction ... he\ncalled A Fall of Moondust \"hard\" science fiction}} {{cite book |last=Hartwell |first=David G.\n|authorlink=David G. Hartwell |coauthors=Kathryn Cramer |title=The Hard SF\nRenaissance |url=|year=2002 |publisher=Tor |location=New York |isbn=0-312-87635-\n1 |pages= |chapter=Introduction: New People, New Places, New Politics\n}} {{cite book |last=Westfahl |first=Gary\n| authorlink = Gary Westfahl\n|title=Cosmic Engineers: A Study of Hard Science Fiction (Contributions to the\nStudy of Science Fiction and Fantasy) |url=http://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0313297274/ref=sib_fs_bod/102-2504711-\n0986542?ie=UTF8&p=S00J&checkSum=ZwwEGNBG6d5NLftyICuVTufBHo5H7Wz8ym1GDkXz0Sk%3D#-\nreader-link |accessdate=2007-10-07 |date=1996-02-28 |publisher=Greenwood Press\n|isbn=0-313-29727-4 |page=2 |chapter=Introduction |quote=hard science fiction\n... the term was first used by P. Schuyler Miller in 1957}} The\ncomplementary term soft science fiction (formed by analogy to \"hard science\nfiction\" {{cite web\n|url=http://www.jessesword.com/sf/view/1843 |title=soft science fiction n. |accessdate=2007-10-\n07 |date=2005-07-25 |work=Science fiction citations |publisher=Jesse's word\n|quote=Soft science fiction, probably a back-formation from Hard Science\nFiction}} ) first appeared in the late 1970s. The term is formed by analogy\nto the popular distinction between the \"hard\" (natural) and \"soft\" (social)\nsciences. The science fiction critic Gary Westfahl argues that neither term is\npart of a rigorous taxonomyâinstead they are approximate ways of characterizing\nstories that reviewers and commentators have found useful. {{Cite book\n| publisher = Blackwell Pub. isbn = 9781405112185 editors = David Seed (ed.)\n| last = Westfahl first = Gary title = A Companion to Science Fiction chapter =\n| Hard Science Fiction location = Malden, MA date = 2008-06-09 url = http://boo-\n| ks.google.com/books?id=PiphRocVYRwC&lpg=PA189&dq=hard%20soft%20science%20fict-\n| ion&pg=PA187#v=onepage&q&f=false accessdate = 2013-02-04 authorlink = Gary\n| Westfahl pages=195â198\n}}\n\nToday, the term \"soft science fiction\" is often used to refer to science fiction\nstories which lack a scientific focus or rigorous adherence to known science.\nThe categorization \"hard science fiction\" represents a position on a broad continuum--\nranging from \"softer\" to \"harder\".\n","linknr":411,"url":"Hard_science_fiction","recorded":1375088705,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hard_science_fiction&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hard_science_fiction&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Ce